Context:
ConfirmationDialog.tsx lines 34-43:
```tsx
const handleAllow = () => {
  if (!current) return;
  onRespond(current.id, 'allow', alwaysAllow || undefined);
  setAlwaysAllow(false);  // resets to false
};

const handleDeny = () => {
  if (!current) return;
  onRespond(current.id, 'deny');
  setAlwaysAllow(false);  // resets to false
};
```

The code resets `alwaysAllow` to false after each action. This test verifies the reset is visible in the UI.

This test naturally combines with US-001 (multiple confirmations):
1. Send two concurrent 'ask' tool calls
2. Toggle the Always Allow switch ON for the first confirmation
3. Click Allow
4. Verify the switch is OFF (unchecked) for the second confirmation
5. Click Deny on the second
6. Verify first tool succeeded, second was denied

```typescript
const dialog = sidePanel.locator('[role="dialog"]');
const alwaysAllowSwitch = dialog.getByRole('switch', { name: 'Always allow this tool' });

// Toggle on
await alwaysAllowSwitch.click();
await expect(alwaysAllowSwitch).toHaveAttribute('data-state', 'checked');

// Allow first confirmation
await sidePanel.getByRole('button', { name: 'Allow' }).click();

// Switch should be unchecked for the second confirmation
await expect(alwaysAllowSwitch).toHaveAttribute('data-state', 'unchecked', { timeout: 5_000 });
```

Constraints:
- This can be combined with the US-001 test or be a separate test — either is fine.
- The Radix Switch uses `data-state='checked'` / `data-state='unchecked'` attributes.

Files:
- e2e/permissions.e2e.ts (add new test)

Context:
The existing badge test at line 513 only tests badge with a single confirmation (shows '1', then clears). The confirmation-badge.ts has thorough unit tests for counting, but the E2E integration (badge visible in real Chrome) is only tested for count=1.

```typescript
test('badge shows correct count for multiple pending confirmations', async ({
  mcpServer, extensionContext, mcpClient,
}) => {
  // Setup: browser permission to 'ask'
  // ... standard setup ...
  const sw = await getBackgroundWorker(extensionContext);
  const sidePanel = await openSidePanel(extensionContext);

  // Three concurrent 'ask' calls
  const [r1, r2, r3] = await Promise.all([
    mcpClient.callTool('browser_list_tabs', {}, { timeout: 60_000 }),
    mcpClient.callTool('browser_list_tabs', {}, { timeout: 60_000 }),
    mcpClient.callTool('browser_list_tabs', {}, { timeout: 60_000 }),
    (async () => {
      // Wait for badge to show '3'
      await waitFor(async () => (await getBadgeText(sw)) === '3', 15_000, 200, 'badge text === "3"');

      // Allow first
      await waitForConfirmationDialog(sidePanel);
      await sidePanel.getByRole('button', { name: 'Allow' }).click();
      await waitFor(async () => (await getBadgeText(sw)) === '2', 10_000, 200, 'badge text === "2"');

      // Allow second
      await sidePanel.getByRole('button', { name: 'Allow' }).click();
      await waitFor(async () => (await getBadgeText(sw)) === '1', 10_000, 200, 'badge text === "1"');

      // Allow third
      await sidePanel.getByRole('button', { name: 'Allow' }).click();
      await waitFor(async () => (await getBadgeText(sw)) === '', 10_000, 200, 'badge text === ""');
    })(),
  ]);

  expect(r1.isError).toBe(false);
  expect(r2.isError).toBe(false);
  expect(r3.isError).toBe(false);
});
```

Note: Three concurrent calls to the same tool is valid — each gets a unique dispatch ID and confirmation ID. The badge count may not reach '3' simultaneously if the first call's confirmation arrives and is displayed before the third call reaches the server. Use `waitFor` with a generous timeout.

Constraints:
- Use three concurrent tool calls, not two — tests the 3+ case which is more thorough.
- Use generous timeouts for badge assertions since the confirmations arrive asynchronously.
